🏗 Section 8: Commercial Models & Governance Alignment

Role & Purpose in the Manual

Section 8 sits at the interface of technical delivery and business accountability. It ensures that the rules of commerce (cost, change requests, funding, contracts) align with the guardrails being built in requirements, quality, and debt management.
In enterprise settings, many delivery disputes arise not from failed engineering but from hidden commercial mismatches. This section aims to make the commerce side explicit, transparent, and defensible.

This section also bridges into the Steering / Governance world: how dashboards, funding visibility, and contract clauses become part of governance rituals.

⸻

🎯 Promise: What This Section Will Deliver

By the end of Section 8, the reader will:
	•	Be able to inject objective cost and budget conversations into evolving requirements.
	•	Understand how to use feature-level estimates as negotiation anchors, with tolerance bands for decomposition variance.
	•	Have model contract clauses and language supporting change, debt, expediency, and risk sharing.
	•	Be able to structure governance forums (Steering, CCB) so commercial risk is surfaced timely.
	•	Know what commercial health dashboards and metrics need to be visible (e.g. burn, funded vs unfunded, forecast delta).
	•	Know how to map alerts and escalations in the commercial track (when cost deviation, underfunded debt, or scope drift exceed thresholds).
	•	Gain confidence in pushing back on “free change” demands based on data and risk.

In short: you will gain the commercial guardrails that ensure delivery integrity doesn’t become a financial liability.

