⚙️ Guidance to the Reader: VP Coaching on Commercial Discipline
	1.	Use Feature-Level Estimation as Anchor
	•	Before decomposing, estimate at Feature granularity with variance bands (±20–30%).
	•	Use this to negotiate scope floor/ceiling early, not after surprises.
	2.	Always Surface Cost of Change Before Saying Yes
	•	When a customer asks for change, don’t immediately commit. Ask: What is the cost, and who will fund it?
	•	Present choices with their cost/risk implications.
	3.	Make the Commercial Health Dashboard a Shared View, Not a Vendor’s Secret
	•	Share burn forecasts, CR exposure, debt, and variance with the Customer Team (appropriately masked).
	•	Build transparency to reduce mistrust.
	4.	Embed Funding Visibility as a Governance Requirement
	•	If a CR is not funded, it doesn’t move.
	•	Escalation must happen if unfunded work passes a threshold (e.g. >10% of current budget).
	5.	Use Contract Clauses to Preempt Disputes, Not Just Legally Defend
	•	Write in clauses for CRs, debt funding, change ownership, escalation triggers.
	•	Make them transparent and part of joint governance, not legal surprises.
	6.	Balance Feature Delivery vs Commercial Clean-up
	•	Don’t ignore commercial drift while building features; adjust scope or ask for rebaseline when misalignment appears.
	7.	Escalate Early When Commercial Health Weakens
	•	If burn deviates beyond tolerance or debt pressure rises unsustainably, escalate to Steering with the evidence.
	•	Avoid letting surprise demands at final delivery.

From the Field: “Once, a cumulative CR exposure of 12% was hidden in spreadsheets until the last quarter. When it got surfaced, the customer thought we were hiding overcharging — trust eroded in a day.”

